# Airbnb JavaScript style guide

### Object and array creation
  - Use literal syntax.
  - Avoid `new Object()` and `new Array()`.

```js
  // Good
  const user = {};
  const numbers = [1, 2, 3];

  // Bad
  const user = new Object();
  const numbers = new Array(1, 2, 3);
```

### Strings
  - Use single quotes `'` unless using template literals.
  - Avoid unnecessary string concatenation.

  ```js
  // Good
  const message = 'Hello, world!';
  const greeting = `Hello, ${name}`;

  // Bad
  const message = "Hello, world!";
  const greeting = "Hello, " + name;
  ```

### Functions

- Use function declarations for named functions.
- Use arrow functions for short callbacks.
- Avoid function expressions unless necessary.

```js
// Good
function getUser(id) {
  return database.findUser(id);
}

const square = (x) => x * x;

// Bad
const getUser = function(id) {
  return database.findUser(id);
};
```

### Arrow functions
  - Use arrow functions for concise syntax.
  - Avoid unnecessary arrow functions.

```js
// Good
const add = (a, b) => a + b;

// Bad
const add = function(a, b) {
  return a + b;
};
```

### Classes and constructors
  - Use `class` syntax.
  - Avoid modifying prototypes manually.

```js
// Good
class Animal {
  constructor(name) {
    this.name = name;
  }
}

// Bad
function Animal(name) {
  this.name = name;
}
```

### Modules
  - Use ES6 module syntax.
  - Avoid `require()` unless using CommonJS.

```js
// Good
import { getUser } from './user';

// Bad
const getUser = require('./user');
```

### Iterators and generators
  - Prefer array methods like `.map()` and `.filter()`.
  - Avoid manual loops when not necessary.

### Properties
  - Use dot notation when possible.
  - Avoid bracket notation unless necessary.

```js
// Good
console.log(user.name);

// Bad
console.log(user["name"]);
```

### Variable Placement and Organization
  - Declare variables at the top of the scope.
  - Group related variables.
 - Follow the variable declaration guidelines in the earlier section (using `const` and `let` appropriately).

```js
// Good
let firstName, lastName;
const age = 30;

// Bad
const age = 30;
let firstName;
```

### Hoisting
  - Be aware that function declarations are hoisted.
  - Don’t rely on hoisting for variables.

### Comparison operators & equality
  - Use `===` and `!==` instead of `==` and `!=`.

```js
// Good
if (a === b) {}

// Bad
if (a == b) {}
```

### Blocks
  - Always use braces `{}` for multi-line statements.

```js
// Good
if (isValid) {
  saveData();
}

// Bad
if (isValid) saveData();
```

### Control statements
  - Prefer `switch` for multiple conditions.

```js
// Good
switch (color) {
  case "red":
    console.log("Stop");
    break;
  case "green":
    console.log("Go");
    break;
  default:
    console.log("Wait");
}
```

### Comments
  - Use meaningful comments.

### Commas
  - Use trailing commas in multi-line objects and arrays.

```js
// Good
const user = {
  name: "Alice",
  age: 25,
};
```

### Semicolons
  - Always use semicolons to end statements.

### Type casting & coercion
  - Use `Number()`, `String()` instead of implicit conversions.

```js
// Good
const num = Number("123");
```

### Naming conventions
  - Use camelCase for variables, PascalCase for classes, and UPPER_CASE for constants.

```js
// Good
const userName = "Alice";
class UserProfile {}
const MAX_USERS = 100;
```

### Accessors
  - Use `get` and `set` for encapsulation.

```js
// Good
class User {
  constructor(name) {
    this._name = name;
  }
  get name() {
    return this._name;
  }
}
```

### Events
  - Use event delegation when possible.

```js
// Good
document.addEventListener("click", (event) => {
  if (event.target.matches(".button")) {
    console.log("Button clicked!");
  }
});
```

### jQuery
  - Prefix jQuery variables with `$`.

```js
// Good
const $button = $(".button");
```

### ECMAScript 6+ features
  - Use ES6+ features wisely, but ensure compatibility.

```js
// Good
const user = { name: "Alice", age: 25 };
const { name, age } = user;
```